\section{Making the Video}

Filming a short movie can take a lot of work. In general, it takes 10 hours of work to produce 1 minute of video. This includes planning, filming, and editing. But if the script is coherent and the B roll is well planned, the process can be much faster. Editting can be the most time consuming part of the process. 

I have found that the best way to edit a movie is to start with the script and the B roll. Then, I add the A roll. Finally, I add the audio. There are lots of software tools available to help with this process and many are free and available on cell phones as apps. However, I also can give you access to the EA studio if you want to use professional software, Adobe Premier Pro. 

In addition, I'll help you with that process. 

\subsection{Basics of Using Adobe Premiere Pro for Video Editing}

Adobe Premiere Pro is a powerful video editing tool that allows you to transform raw footage into a polished, professional video. Here's a basic overview to get started with editing your climate change video:

\subsubsection{Setting Up a New Project}  

When starting a new project:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Open Premiere Pro and select \textbf{New Project}.
    \item Name your project and select a location to save the project file.
    \item Choose your video settings (e.g., frame rate, resolution). For YouTube, 1080p (1920x1080) at 30 fps is a common setting.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Importing Footage}  

To add video clips:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Select \textbf{File} $>$ \textbf{Import} to bring in your A-roll and B-roll footage.
    \item Drag and drop the clips into the project timeline.
    \item Use the \textbf{Media Browser} to locate other media files such as images or audio.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Editing Your Timeline}  

Once you have your clips in the timeline:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Use the \textbf{Razor Tool} to cut clips and remove unnecessary footage.
    \item Drag clips around in the timeline to adjust their order and pacing.
    \item Use \textbf{Transitions} (e.g., fade in/out, cross dissolve) between clips to create smooth changes.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Adding Audio}  

To add audio:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Import your background music and sound effects.
    \item Drag the audio to the audio track in the timeline.
    \item Adjust the audio levels to ensure your voiceover or interview audio is clear over the background music.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Adding Titles and Text Overlays}  

To add text:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Select the \textbf{Text Tool} and click on the program monitor to create a text box.
    \item Customize the font, size, and color of the text to fit the theme of your video.
    \item Use \textbf{Essential Graphics} panel for pre-made templates for more professional-looking titles.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Color Correction and Effects}  

To improve the look of your video:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Use the \textbf{Lumetri Color} panel to adjust exposure, contrast, and color balance.
    \item Add effects from the \textbf{Effects Panel} to enhance visual interest (e.g., slow motion, sharpen, etc.).
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Exporting Your Final Video}  

When you’re ready to export:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Select \textbf{File} $>$ \textbf{Export} $>$ \textbf{Media}.
    \item Choose the H.264 format for YouTube-compatible files.
    \item Select the \textbf{YouTube 1080p Full HD} preset, or customize the settings for optimal resolution and file size.
    \item Click \textbf{Export} to render your video.
\end{itemize}








